p, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gaste","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and French: metonymic occupational name or nickname for a turnspit, i.e. a servant who turned the spit (or, as a French surname, for a seller of roast meat), from Old French <i>haste</i> ‘(roasting) spit’. This surname is very rare in France.","History: A bearer of the surname <i>Haste</i> from Paris, France, is documented in Montreal, QC, in 1662. He apparently had no offspring."],"variants":[{"name":"Hast","meanings":["German: probably a habitational name from Haste near Wunstorf or Osnabrück.","Swedish: soldier's name, from <i>hast</i> ‘haste, hurry’.","English: variant of   Haste  ."]},{"name":"Aste","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Haste  ."]}]},{"name":"Nigel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval name <i>Nigellus</i>, a Latinized version (ostensibly representing a diminutive of Latin <i>niger</i> ‘black’) of the vernacular <i>Ni(h)el</i>, i.e.   Neil .  Although it is frequently found in medieval records, this form was probably not used in everyday life before its revival by antiquarians such as  Sir Walter  Scott in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nigel de Gaste was born in 1126, in Wiltshire, England, his father, Sir Robert Meurdracs de Gaste, was 25 and his mother, de Geroie, was 26. He married Lady Nigel De Gaste about 1150. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1186, in Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 60, and was buried in Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{